# Convert the Customer_ID column to a factor/category
Initial_dataset['Customer_ID'] = Initial_dataset['Customer_ID'].astype('category')

# Calculate the median Inhand Salary by customer using groupby and summarize
median_Inhand_salary_by_customer = Initial_dataset.groupby('Customer_ID').agg(median_salary=('Monthly_Inhand_Salary', 'median'))

# Join the median salary column to the dataset
Initial_dataset = pd.merge(Initial_dataset, median_Inhand_salary_by_customer, on='Customer_ID', how='left')

# Replace missing values in Monthly Inhand Salary column with median salary
Initial_dataset['Monthly_Inhand_Salary'].fillna(Initial_dataset['median_salary'], inplace=True)

# Drop the median salary column
Initial_dataset.drop('median_salary', axis=1, inplace=True)

Outcome

  • The Missing Values for Monthly_Inhand_Salary are imputed with the Median_Values based on each Customer_ID.
  • Median value is opted as there might be some higher monthly salary which might lead to abnormal results if we use mean for calculating salary.

In [41]:
# Define function to convert string to number of months
def convert_to_months(s):
    # If value is null or empty, return default value 0
    if pd.isna(s) or s.strip() == "":
        return 0
    # Split string into years and months
    years, months = s.split(" Years and ")
    months = months.replace(" Months", "")
    # Convert to total months
    total_months = int(years) * 12 + int(months)
    return total_months

# Apply the function to the "age" column and create a new column "age_in_months"
Initial_dataset["Credit_History_Age"] = Initial_dataset["Credit_History_Age"].apply(convert_to_months)
In [42]:
# Calculate the median credit history age by customer using groupby and summarize
median_credit_history_age_customer = Initial_dataset.groupby('Customer_ID').agg(median_credit_history_age=('Credit_History_Age', 'median'))

# Join the median credit history age column to the dataset
Initial_dataset = pd.merge(Initial_dataset, median_credit_history_age_customer, on='Customer_ID', how='left')

# Replace rows with a value of 0 in Credit History Age column with median credit history age
Initial_dataset['Credit_History_Age'] = Initial_dataset['Credit_History_Age'].apply(lambda x: Initial_dataset['median_credit_history_age'][x] if x == 0 else x)

# Drop the median credit history age column
Initial_dataset.drop('median_credit_history_age', axis=1, inplace=True)

Outcome:

  • The column values are converted to just month values and the data type is changed from object to numeric.

#Checking for indexes where Monthly_Balance is less than 0 (Negative)
Initial_dataset.index[Initial_dataset['Monthly_Balance'] < 0].tolist()
Out[55]:
[5545, 26177, 29158, 35570, 60009, 75251, 83255]
In [56]:
#Based on the above cell results it is evident only 8 Values are negative for the Monthly_Balance so replacing those with '0'
Initial_dataset.Monthly_Balance= Initial_dataset.Monthly_Balance.mask(Initial_dataset.Monthly_Balance.lt(0),0)
In [57]:
# Calculate the median Monthly_Balance by customer using groupby and summarize
median_Monthly_Balance_customer = Initial_dataset.groupby('Customer_ID').agg(median_Monthly_Balance=('Monthly_Balance', 'median'))

# Join the median Monthly_Balance column to the dataset
Initial_dataset = pd.merge(Initial_dataset, median_Monthly_Balance_customer, on='Customer_ID', how='left')

# Replace missing values in Num of Monthly_Balance column with median delayed payments
Initial_dataset['Monthly_Balance'].fillna(Initial_dataset['median_Monthly_Balance'], inplace=True)

# Drop the median Monthly_Balance column
Initial_dataset.drop('median_Monthly_Balance', axis=1, inplace=True)

Outcome

  • The _ values are replaced by Empty spaces.
  • The data type is converted to Numeric(Float).
  • Negative values are replaced with 0.
  • The null values are replaced with Median values based on Customer ID.

median_Num_of_Loan_customer = Clean_dataset.groupby('Customer_ID').agg(median_Num_of_Loan=('Num_of_Loan', 'median'))

In [151]:
# Find the optimal number of clusters using the elbow method
distortions = []
for i in range(1, 11):
    kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters=i, random_state=0)
    kmeans.fit(pca_X_train)
    distortions.append(kmeans.inertia_)
    
# Plot the elbow curve
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
plt.plot(range(1, 11), distortions, marker='o')
plt.xlabel('Number of clusters')
plt.ylabel('Distortion')
plt.show()

Observation

  • Based on the Elbow Method we can identify that the number of cluster that fits for KMean Clustering is 3.
In [152]:
# From the elbow curve, select the optimal number of clusters
k = 3

# Apply K-Means clustering on the training dataset
kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters=k, random_state=0)
kmeans.fit(pca_X_train)
train_cluster_labels = kmeans.labels_
centroids = kmeans.cluster_centers_

# Add the cluster labels as additional features to the training dataset
pca_X_train['cluster_label'] = train_cluster_labels

# Apply K-Means clustering on the testing dataset
test_cluster_labels = kmeans.predict(pca_X_test)

# Add the cluster labels as additional features to the testing dataset
pca_X_test['cluster_label'] = test_cluster_labels

# Calculate the silhouette score for the training dataset
silhouette_avg = silhouette_score(pca_X_train, train_cluster_labels)
print(f"Silhouette score for {k} clusters: {silhouette_avg}")

10.2.4 Performane evaluation of the model¶
  • Precision: Precision measures the fraction of positive predictions that are correct.
  • Recall: Recall measures the fraction of positive instances that are correctly predicted.
  • F1 Score: F1 score is the harmonic mean of precision and recall.
In [207]:
evaluator = MulticlassClassificationEvaluator(labelCol="Credit_Score", predictionCol="prediction", metricName="weightedPrecision")
precision = evaluator.evaluate(predictions)
evaluator = MulticlassClassificationEvaluator(labelCol="Credit_Score", predictionCol="prediction", metricName="weightedRecall")
recall = evaluator.evaluate(predictions)
evaluator = MulticlassClassificationEvaluator(labelCol="Credit_Score", predictionCol="prediction", metricName="f1")
f1 = evaluator.evaluate(predictions)

print("Precision: {:.3f}".format(precision))
print("Recall: {:.3f}".format(recall))
print("F1 score: {:.3f}".format(f1))

Precision: 0.696

  • F1 Score: F1 score is the harmonic mean of precision and recall.

10.5 Hyperparameter Tunning on best performing dataset¶

In [209]:
# Import balanced Train and Test Dataset since it performed better than other datasets

In [213]:

In [214]:

In [216]:
# Define the hyperparameter grid
param_grid = ParamGridBuilder() \
    .addGrid(hyper_rf.numTrees, [90,110]) \
    .addGrid(hyper_rf.maxDepth, [5, 15]) \
    .build()

                          estimatorParamMaps=param_grid,
                          evaluator=evaluator,
                          numFolds=5,
                          seed=42)
